The paper discusses the integration of a self-healing mechanism onto printed circuit boards, which involves the use of conductive particles dispersed in an insulating fluid to physically restore fractured interconnects in electronic circuits. This topic falls under the category of "embedded systems" (cs.ET) and "neural and evolutionary computing" (cs.NE) as the healing mechanism is driven by an electric field and has the ability to solve mazes. Additionally, the paper discusses the influence of the geometry of conductive particles and terminal impedances on the healing efficiency, which relates to the sub-categories of "robotics" (cs.RO), "electromagnetism" (cs.EM), and "modeling and simulation" (cs.MS).
